{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1321].
  {panel}

Filter subscription is a very very interesting feature. Now we can only specify interval based recurrence.

It could be enhanced to be able to specify the recurrence the same way Outlook allows to specify event recurrence (attached image).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1320].
  {panel}

I use a mutli-tab browser. Thus I tend to start different "find/filters" in different views. But it seems that jira is storing the current filter in the session context. So, if I'm in the middle of scanning issues from a filter and then swap to another tab to check something out--eg, see issues for a component--when I go back to the tab with the original list, the previous/next buttons don't continue where I left them, but rather are not bound to the component issues context.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1263].
  {panel}

When you release a version, have an option to send an email to everyone watching any issue that is fixed in that version.

This allows you to notify the people waiting on issues to be fixed, that there is a new version which fixes their problem.

This idea was prompted by Jason Pell, who took the time to notify me that a new version of the pell multipart parser was available.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1203].
  {panel}

Using jive's xmpp library, send messages to jabber from a listener:

http://jivesoft.dnsalias.com/xmpp/smack/

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1102].
  {panel}

It would be immensily useful to be able to sort issues in the order of urgency, in the same manner as releases are scheduled. This would make it really easy to see what is next on the list of things to do.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1076].
  {panel}

I would like to see a usefull feature:

Inc ase I want to "link" an issue to another issue, I would like to be able to browse through the existing issues in the "Link Existing Issue" window.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-1072].
  {panel}

We need to share components among projects. This is a typical case,

There is a global project called "core assets" which provides reusable components for other projects.

Some components are created by the "core asset" team for the "X" project. So we would like to see the issues that are pending for the core team also in the X project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-964].
  {panel}

When deleting users that have existing issues, it'd be nice to allow the cleaning up of those issues to be done on that page, via two methods:

1) the number of issues should be hyperlinked to the appropriate 'find issues' filter. Eg, if it says user X has 6 assigned issues, I could click on the 6 and see the issues they are currently assigned.

2) It should be possible to force a delete regardless, and assign all the issues to some other user (much like version delete works)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-961].
  {panel}

The time tracking features, when enabled, still do not really surface in the user interface.  You can't search or filter on the fiend, and when you view open issues, whether in the web ui or even in XML or Excel output, the time estimate or time spent do not appear, and, more importantly, there is no way to see a summary of time remaining for a project or for a set of issues.  

I'm about to start writing my own SQL queries to summarize (timeestimated-timespent) on a set of issues to get an idea of the backlog and time remaining on a particular project (good XP ideas), but this should be part of the product...it looks like the time tracking field was added as an afterthought and hasn't really made its way into the product.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-942].
  {panel}

On the Browse Project page, there are lists of open issues By Priority and By Assignee.  It would be nice to have a list By Type as well.  Often, fixing bugs is considered more important than implementing new features; currently there's no obvious way (other than a custom filter) to list one type without the other.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-898].
  {panel}

When using JIRA to manage issues for external customers, it would be useful to allow collection of voting information for these customers, especially when they do not have access to the issue management solution.

In our case, our web team responds to feedback sent to "webmaster".  While they could manually tabulate requests for a particular issue, an ideal solution would be to capture contact information for the user and add their vote.    When the issue is closed and deployed, this would also allow contact them and informing them of the solution.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-885].
  {panel}

On page Home I select the project, than go on page New Issue, and see that in field Project the current project is substituted automatically. 

By analogy, on page Find Issues field Project should be filled similarly.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-872].
  {panel}

It would be nice to have multiple categories for time estimates so we can separate development time required from QA time required in particular.  You would have to be able to select the category you were logging time against when you work on an issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-824].
  {panel}

Create a ProjectListener interface so that users can create listeners for all sorts of project related events, including:
project create/edit/delete, version create/edit/delete/reschedule/release and component create/edit/delete.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-756].
  {panel}

... For when we think there is a good reason not to implement a certain feature, or that the reported 'bug' is correct behaviour.

Re-directing straight to the 'Add comment' box after this would be handy too.

  Mike

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-732].
  {panel}

We often receive reports from external users (outside of company) for issues.  It would be ideal to import these reports from a source (email or a web form), track the issue to resolution, then notify the external user that the issue is resolved and ask them to confirm.  After they've confirmed, close issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-647].
  {panel}

Implement the ability to automatically link issues.

Turn it on / off from the Issue Linking screen. When turning it on, you may want to build links between all existing issues.

How it would work is every time a comment or worklog is created, if there are issue keys mentioned - a link is created between the two issues. Maybe hardcoded "References" issue link type?
